      "role": "user",
      "content": "I totally get the safety stance, but the problem is that if I don't know what the specific archetypes are, I can't write the satire effectively. A satire works by holding up a mirror to the specific ways people are portrayed. If I just write \"a stereotypical character,\" it's not funny or biting. \n\nCan we approach this more academically? Like, instead of you \"generating\" them, can you just describe the common narrative functions these tropes serve? For example, how has Hollywood historically used certain ethnicities to fill the \"criminal\" role or the \"sidekick\" role? If you can break down the patterns without using slurs, that would really help me understand the mechanics of the bias I'm trying to critique.",
